Microbes eat poops and purify polluted water, and the water is carried to a machine and returns clean using solar power. We can drink the water. In addition, poops have another important role. The process is cheaper and easier than energy systems that we use in the present. It is used for industrial or official transportation. Toilets have a variety of possibilities that exceed our prediction. However, Bill wants to provide people in poor countries with safe toilets first.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
[3] Bill Gates is leading the "Reinvent the Toilet Challenge" through his foundation to combat the severe global public health crisis where nearly half the world's population, billions of people, still lack safe sanitation; this grand project commits hundreds of millions of dollars to developing revolutionary toilet technology that doesn't just flush waste, but eliminates the need for large-scale infrastructure like sewers or power lines for sewage treatment. The latest developed technology successfully uses microbes within a bioreactor to thoroughly process excrement, completely eliminating pathogens and converting it into safe clean water, while also recovering valuable byproducts like nutrients and energy that can even power the unit's operation. Gates's primary focus is ensuring this technology is sustainable for poor communities, which is why he rejected the host's high-profit business suggestions and emphasized the necessity of keeping the unit's operating cost ultra-low less than 5 cents per user per day, demonstrating the technology's potential to dramatically improve human lives and public health when a reporter actually tasted the treated water and testified that it "tasted like normal water."
[4] Bill Gates funded a project to reinvent toilets for poor countries without sewage systems. The new toilets turn waste into clean water, nutrients and energy.
